\begin{abstract}
We derive an expression for the cosmological constant arising from the
spectral density of a discrete quantum vacuum described by a Hamiltonian
crystal. In this framework spacetime emerges from a lattice of quantum
modes whose spectral gaps determine the vacuum energy density. The
cosmological constant is shown to be directly proportional to the
integrated spectral density of the vacuum Hamiltonian. Possible
extensions involving hierarchical spectra, prime distributions, and
Riemann-zero spectra are discussed.
\end{abstract}

\section{Quantum Vacuum Hamiltonian}

We assume spacetime emerges from a discrete quantum system with vacuum
modes labeled by $n$. The fundamental Hamiltonian is

\begin{equation}
H_{\mathrm{crystal}}
=
\sum_{n} \Delta E_n \, a_n^\dagger a_n
+
H_{\mathrm{int}}
\end{equation}

where

\begin{itemize}
\item $a_n^\dagger, a_n$ are creation and annihilation operators,
\item $\Delta E_n$ are spectral gaps,
\item $H_{\mathrm{int}}$ represents interactions between modes.
\end{itemize}

The vacuum lattice has characteristic spacing

\begin{equation}
l_c
\end{equation}

which defines the fundamental cell volume.

\section{Vacuum Ground State}

The vacuum satisfies

\begin{equation}
a_n |0\rangle = 0
\end{equation}

However each quantum oscillator contributes zero-point energy

\begin{equation}
E_{0,n} = \frac{1}{2} \Delta E_n .
\end{equation}

Thus the total vacuum energy becomes

\begin{equation}
E_0 =
\sum_n \frac{1}{2}\Delta E_n .
\end{equation}

\section{Vacuum Energy Density}

If a lattice cell has volume

\begin{equation}
V_c = l_c^3
\end{equation}

then the vacuum energy density is

\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathrm{vac}}
=
\frac{E_0}{V_c}
=
\frac{1}{2l_c^3}
\sum_n \Delta E_n .
\end{equation}

\section{Einstein Equation with Cosmological Constant}

The Einstein field equation including a cosmological constant is

\begin{equation}
R_{\mu\nu}
-
\frac{1}{2}R g_{\mu\nu}
+
\Lambda g_{\mu\nu}
=
8\pi G T_{\mu\nu}.
\end{equation}

Vacuum energy behaves like a stress-energy tensor

\begin{equation}
T_{\mu\nu}^{(\mathrm{vac})}
=
-\rho_{\mathrm{vac}} g_{\mu\nu}.
\end{equation}

Thus the cosmological constant satisfies

\begin{equation}
\Lambda = 8\pi G \rho_{\mathrm{vac}}.
\end{equation}

\section{Hamiltonian Crystal Expression}

Substituting the vacuum density yields

\begin{equation}
\Lambda
=
8\pi G
\left(
\frac{1}{2l_c^3}
\sum_n \Delta E_n
\right).
\end{equation}

Simplifying,

\begin{equation}
\boxed{
\Lambda
=
\frac{4\pi G}{l_c^3}
\sum_n \Delta E_n
}
\end{equation}

which expresses the cosmological constant directly in terms of the
vacuum spectral gaps.

\section{Spectral Density Formulation}

Define the spectral density

\begin{equation}
g(E) = \sum_n \delta(E-\Delta E_n).
\end{equation}

Then

\begin{equation}
\sum_n \Delta E_n
=
\int_0^\infty E\,g(E)\,dE.
\end{equation}

The cosmological constant becomes

\begin{equation}
\boxed{
\Lambda
=
\frac{4\pi G}{l_c^3}
\int_0^\infty E\,g(E)\,dE
}
\end{equation}

showing that dark energy is determined by the vacuum spectral
distribution.

\section{Hierarchical Spectral Model}

Suppose the spectral gaps follow

\begin{equation}
\Delta E_n = E_* \epsilon^n
\end{equation}

with $0<\epsilon\ll1$.

Then

\begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \Delta E_n
=
E_* \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \epsilon^n
=
\frac{E_*}{1-\epsilon}.
\end{equation}

For small $\epsilon$ this naturally suppresses the vacuum energy.

\section{Time-Dependent Vacuum}

If the vacuum modes are periodically driven,

\begin{equation}
V(t)
=
\sum_n \delta_n a_n^\dagger a_n \cos(\omega t),
\end{equation}

then

\begin{equation}
H(t) = H_{\mathrm{crystal}} + V(t).
\end{equation}

The vacuum energy density becomes

\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathrm{vac}}(t)
=
\rho_0
+
\Delta\rho \cos(\omega t).
\end{equation}

Thus

\begin{equation}
\Lambda(t)
=
\Lambda_0
+
\Delta\Lambda \cos(\omega t).
\end{equation}

\section{Prime Spectrum Extension}

If spectral gaps follow prime numbers,

\begin{equation}
\Delta E_n = \alpha \log p_n
\end{equation}

where $p_n$ is the $n$th prime, then the prime number theorem

\begin{equation}
\pi(x) \sim \frac{x}{\log x}
\end{equation}

implies controlled growth of the vacuum spectral sum.

\section{Riemann-Zero Spectrum}

If spectral gaps correspond to the imaginary parts of zeros of the
Riemann zeta function,

\begin{equation}
\zeta\left(\frac{1}{2}+i\gamma_n\right)=0
\end{equation}

then

\begin{equation}
\Delta E_n = \gamma_n
\end{equation}

and the vacuum energy becomes

\begin{equation}
\rho_{\mathrm{vac}}
=
\frac{1}{2l_c^3}
\sum_n \gamma_n .
\end{equation}

\section{Conclusion}

The Hamiltonian crystal framework provides a direct link between the
cosmological constant and the spectral density of the vacuum Hamiltonian.
In this picture dark energy arises from the residual zero-point energy
of discrete vacuum modes. Extensions involving hierarchical spectra,
prime-number distributions, and Riemann-zero spectra suggest deep
connections between cosmology, quantum theory, and number theory.

